> The author completely missed the point of named parameters.<p>The author didn&#x27;t miss the point of named parameters. At no point does the author even cover the point of named parameters. The author complains that:<p>1. they&#x27;re inconsistent, all parameters <i>but the first</i> are named by default <i>and</i> named parameters are still positional (you can&#x27;t reorder &quot;named&quot; parameters in the callsite)<p>2. making parameters purely positional is non-obvious and ugly<p>And he missed the part which takes the cake: Swift doesn&#x27;t actually have <i>named</i> parameter, parameters 1+ are <i>labelled</i> (#1), and labels and names are independent, you can define this:<p><pre><code>    func foo(a b: Int, c d: Int) { … }
</code></pre>
which is called with a:c:, but the bindings are on b and d. You can also define this:<p><pre><code>    func foo(a b: Int, _ d: Int) { … }
</code></pre>
which is called as `foo(a:5, 7)` which while somewhat consistent is really garbage.
